const Q_ECONOMICS_2018_MODEL_I=[{"id": "objective>Economics>2018 Model I>1", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Who is the 'lender of the last resort' in the banking structure of Nigeria?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Diamond Bank PLC</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Central Bank of Nigeria</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">First Bank PLC</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Union Bank of Nigeria PLC</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The 'lender of the last resort' in the banking structure of Nigeria is the Central Bank of Nigeria. This institution provides financial institutions with emergency liquidity when they face short-term funding issues, ensuring stability in the financial system.</div>", "topic": "FINANCIAL INSTITUTION : CENTRAL BANK"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2018 Model I>2", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Scarcity is a condition that exists when </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">there is a fixed supply of resources</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">there is a large demand for a product</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">resources are not able to meet the entire demand for a product</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">all of the above</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Scarcity is defined as a condition where resources are insufficient to meet the demand for a product. This means that while there may be a demand for a product, the available resources are not enough to satisfy that demand. Therefore, the correct answer is that resources are not able to meet the entire demand for a product.</div>", "topic": "BASIC ECONOMIC PROBLEMS"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2018 Model I>3", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The market form in which there is only one producer is called</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Unfair competition</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Monopoly</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Oligopoly</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Imperfect competition</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The market form in which there is only one producer is called a 'Monopoly'. In a monopoly, a single firm dominates the market, which allows it to set prices and control supply without competition.</div>", "topic": "MARKET STRUCTURE : IMPERFECT MARKET - MONOPOLY"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2018 Model I>4", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Which of the following taxes is a progressive tax?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Income tax</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Custom tax</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Sales tax</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Excise duty</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">A progressive tax is one where the tax rate increases as the taxable amount increases. Income tax is a classic example of a progressive tax, as higher income earners pay a higher percentage of their income in taxes compared to lower income earners.</div>", "topic": "PUBLIC FINANCE : CLASSIFICATION OF TAX"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2018 Model I>5", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Find the median of the following percentages: 43%, 76%, 64%, 37%, 76%, 54%</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">64%</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">54%</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">118%</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">59%</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">To find the median, first arrange the percentages in ascending order: 37%, 43%, 54%, 64%, 76%, 76%. The median is the average of the two middle numbers (54% and 64%) since there is an even number of observations. Thus, the median is (54% + 64%) / 2 = 59%. Therefore, the correct answer is 59%.</div>", "topic": "TOOLS FOR ECONOMIC ANALYSIS : MEASURE OF CENTRAL TENDENCY"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2018 Model I>6", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Selecting from available alternative is </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">choice</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">scarcity</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">opportunity cost</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">scale of preference</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Selecting from available alternatives is referred to as 'choice' in economics. It involves making decisions based on preferences and available options.</div>", "topic": "BASIC CONCEPTS OF ECONOMICS"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2018 Model I>7", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Which of the following is not an aim of the agricultural produce board ?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Stabilizing the price of agricultural product</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Arrangement of the buying and selling of the product in the international market</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Undertaking projects that help to improve upon the method of production</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Discouraging research funding to aid production</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The agricultural produce board aims to stabilize prices, facilitate buying and selling in international markets, and improve production methods. Discouraging research funding contradicts the goal of improving production methods, making it the correct answer as it is not an aim of the board.</div>", "topic": "AGRICULTURE IN WEST AFRICA : MARKETING BOARDS"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2018 Model I>8", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">When total utility reaches its maximum, then marginal utility will be</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Minimum</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Average</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Zero</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Negative</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">When total utility reaches its maximum, marginal utility will be zero. This is because marginal utility measures the additional satisfaction gained from consuming one more unit of a good. At maximum total utility, consuming more would not increase satisfaction, hence marginal utility is zero. Therefore, option C is correct.</div>", "topic": "THEORY OF CONSUMER BEHAVIOUR : MARGINAL RATE OF SUBSTITUTION -MRS"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2018 Model I>9", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Resources are scarce in relations to</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">choice</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the demand for them</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">unlimited wants</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">their scale of preference</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Resources are scarce in relation to 'unlimited wants'. Scarcity refers to the fundamental economic problem of having seemingly unlimited human wants in a world of limited resources. This imbalance necessitates choices and prioritization in resource allocation.</div>", "topic": "INTRODUCTION TO ECONOMICS"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2018 Model I>10", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The law of diminishing marginal utility applies to a </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Firm to minimizes cost</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Consumer who maximizes satisfaction</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Producer who maximizes marginal product</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Consumer who minimizes total utility</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The law of diminishing marginal utility states that as a consumer consumes more units of a good, the additional satisfaction (utility) gained from each additional unit decreases. This concept applies specifically to consumers who are maximizing their satisfaction, as they will continue to consume until the marginal utility of the last unit consumed is equal to the price paid for it. Therefore, the correct option is 'Consumer who maximizes satisfaction'.</div>", "topic": "THEORY OF CONSUMER BEHAVIOUR : DIMINISHING MARGINAL UTILITY AND LAW OF DEMAND"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2018 Model I>11", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Find the mean of 8, 3, 5, 2, 7, 5, 7, 3, 6, 7</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">5.1</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">5.2</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">5.3</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">5.4</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">To find the mean, sum all the numbers and divide by the count of numbers. The sum of the numbers 8, 3, 5, 2, 7, 5, 7, 3, 6, 7 is 53. There are 10 numbers, so the mean is 53/10 = 5.3. Therefore, the correct answer is 5.3.</div>", "topic": "TOOLS FOR ECONOMIC ANALYSIS : MEASURE OF CENTRAL TENDENCY"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2018 Model I>12", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Which of the following is not considered as a factor of production?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">money</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">machinery</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">land</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">unskilled labour</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Money is not considered a factor of production. The factors of production typically include land, labor, and capital (machinery). Money is a medium of exchange and does not directly contribute to the production of goods and services.</div>", "topic": "FACTORS OF PRODUCTION AND THEIR THEORIES"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2018 Model I>13", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the short run, when the output of a firm increases, its average fixed cost</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Remains constant</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Decreases</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Increases</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">First decreases and then rises</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the short run, as a firm's output increases, its average fixed cost decreases. This is because average fixed cost is calculated by dividing total fixed costs by the quantity of output produced. As output increases, the same total fixed costs are spread over a larger number of units, leading to a lower average fixed cost.</div>", "topic": "THEORY OF COST AND REVENUE"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2018 Model I>14", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">A retailer is a middle man between</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the wholesaler and consumers</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the manufacturers and consumers</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the government and her agencies</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">all of the above</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">A retailer is primarily a middleman between the manufacturers and consumers. Retailers purchase goods from manufacturers or wholesalers and sell them directly to consumers, making option B the most accurate.</div>", "topic": "DISTRIBUTIVE TRADE : THE RETAILER"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2018 Model I>15", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The bar chart shows the distribution of primary classes 1 - 6 in Montessori Primary School. Use the information and answer the question below. <br/> <img src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" style=\"position:relative;max-width:100%;\"/> <br/>  <br/> How many pupils are in the school?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">200</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">300</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">400</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">500</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">To determine the number of the pupils in the scholl, add each rectangular bar together for each classes i.e class 1 comprises of 80 pupils, class 2 is 60, class 3 is 60, class 4 is 40, class 5 is 40 and class 6 is 20.  <br/>  <br/> Add it together, 80 +60 +60 +40 +40 +20 <br/> = 300</div>", "topic": "TOOLS FOR ECONOMIC ANALYSIS : SCIENTIFIC APPROACH"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2018 Model I>16", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> The bar chart shows the distribution of primary classes 1 - 6 in Montessori Primary School. Use the information and answer the question below. <br/> <img src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" style=\"position:relative;max-width:100%;\"/> <br/> If each pupil gets three exercise books, how many exercise books are needed?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">600</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">700</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">800</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">900</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">class 1 comprises of 80 pupils, class 2 is 60, class 3 is 60, class 4 is 40, class 5 is 40 and class 6 is 20.  <br/>  <br/> Therefore, each with three exercise books will be: <br/>  <br/> 80 x 3 + 60  x 3 + 60 x 3 + 40 x 3 + 40 x 3 + 20 x 3 <br/> = 240 + 180 +180 + 120 +120 + 60 <br/> = 900</div>", "topic": "TOOLS FOR ECONOMIC ANALYSIS : SCIENTIFIC APPROACH"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2018 Model I>17", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> The bar chart shows the distribution of primary classes 1 - 6 in Montessori Primary School. Use the information and answer the question below. <br/> <img src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" style=\"position:relative;max-width:100%;\"/> <br/> If an exercise book costs #20, how much is spent altogether on exercise books?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">#18,000</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">#20,000</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">#16,000</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">#14,000</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">class 1 comprises of 80 pupils, class 2 is 60, class 3 is 60, class 4 is 40, class 5 is 40 and class 6 is 20.  <br/>  <br/> Therefore, each with three exercise books will be: <br/>  <br/> 80 x 3 + 60  x 3 + 60 x 3 + 40 x 3 + 40 x 3 + 20 x 3 <br/> = 240 + 180 +180 + 120 +120 + 60 <br/> Total = 900 <br/>  <br/> If an exercise book costs #20, then 900  x  20 <br/> = #18,000</div>", "topic": "TOOLS FOR ECONOMIC ANALYSIS : SCIENTIFIC APPROACH"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2018 Model I>18", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">When a market is in equilibrium</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Quantity demanded equals quantity supply</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Excess demand and excess supply are zero</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The market is cleared by the equilibrium price</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">All of the above</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">When a market is in equilibrium, it means that the quantity demanded equals the quantity supplied, excess demand and excess supply are zero, and the market is cleared by the equilibrium price. Therefore, option D, which states 'All of the above', is correct.</div>", "topic": "MARKET STRUCTURE : MEANING OF MARKET & TYPES"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2018 Model I>19", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The quantity of a product sellers are willing to sell is affected by</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the price of the product</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the quantity of the product available</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the quantity produced</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the demand schedule</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The quantity of a product that sellers are willing to sell is primarily affected by the price of the product. According to the law of supply, as the price of a product increases, the quantity supplied also increases, and vice versa. This relationship is fundamental in economics.</div>", "topic": "THEORY OF SUPPLY : MEANING AND DETERMINANTS"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2018 Model I>20", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">An individual demand curve slopes downward to the right because of the </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Working of the law of diminishing marginal utility</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Substitution effect of decrease in price</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Income effect of fall in price</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">All of the above</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">An individual demand curve slopes downward to the right due to the law of diminishing marginal utility, the substitution effect, and the income effect. The law of diminishing marginal utility states that as a consumer consumes more of a good, the additional satisfaction (utility) gained from consuming each additional unit decreases. The substitution effect occurs when a decrease in the price of a good makes it more attractive compared to other goods, leading consumers to substitute it for those other goods. The income effect refers to the change in consumption resulting from a change in real income or purchasing power when the price of a good changes. Therefore, all of the above factors contribute to the downward slope of the demand curve.</div>", "topic": "THEORY OF DEMAND : MEANING AND DETERMINANTS"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2018 Model I>21", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Which of these banks is the apex in Nigeria?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">First bank</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Zenith bank</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Central bank</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Bank of industry</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The apex bank in Nigeria is the Central Bank of Nigeria (CBN). It is responsible for regulating the monetary and financial system in the country, overseeing the banking sector, and formulating monetary policy.</div>", "topic": "FINANCIAL INSTITUTION : CENTRAL BANK"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2018 Model I>22", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">A consumer purchasing commodity x will maximize his satisfaction if </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Px = MUx</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Px > MUx</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Px ≥ MUx</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Px < Mux</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">A consumer purchasing commodity x will maximize satisfaction when the price of the commodity (Px) is equal to or less than the marginal utility (MUx) derived from that commodity. This is represented by the condition Px ≥ MUx, meaning that the consumer will continue to purchase the commodity until the price equals the marginal utility.</div>", "topic": "THEORY OF DEMAND : MEANING AND DETERMINANTS"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2018 Model I>23", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">A firm that charges different prices for goods and services that have the same technical qualities is called</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Perfect competitior</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Monopsony</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Oligopoly</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Discriminating monopoly</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">A firm that charges different prices for goods and services that have the same technical qualities is known as a 'Discriminating monopoly'. This practice is called price discrimination, where a seller charges different prices to different consumers for the same product based on their willingness to pay.</div>", "topic": "MARKET STRUCTURE : IMPERFECT MARKET - MONOPOLY"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2018 Model I>24", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Assume that  number of sellers in the market  for good X both falls. Based on this information, we can conclude with certainty that the equilibrium</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Price will decrease</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Price will increase</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Quantity will decrease</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Quantity will increase</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">When the number of sellers in the market for a good decreases, the supply of that good decreases. According to the law of supply and demand, a decrease in supply, with demand remaining constant, leads to an increase in the equilibrium price. Therefore, we can conclude that the equilibrium price will increase.</div>", "topic": "MARKET STRUCTURE"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2018 Model I>25", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The economist's objections to monopoly rest on which of the following grounds?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">There is a transfer of income from consumers to the monopolist</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">There is welfare loss as resources tend to be misallocated under monopoly</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Only A is correct</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Both A and B are correct</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The economist's objections to monopoly rest on the grounds that there is a transfer of income from consumers to the monopolist and that there is welfare loss as resources tend to be misallocated under monopoly. Both points highlight the negative impacts of monopolistic practices on market efficiency and consumer welfare.</div>", "topic": "MARKET STRUCTURE : IMPERFECT MARKET - MONOPOLY"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2018 Model I>26", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Money can serve these functions</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">measure of deferred payment</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">store of value</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">A only</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">A and B above</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Money serves multiple functions, including being a measure of deferred payment and a store of value. Therefore, both A and B are correct, making option D the right choice.</div>", "topic": "MONEY : FUNCTIONS OF MONEY"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2018 Model I>27", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">A supply curve is directly affected by</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Technology</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Input costs</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Government regulation</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">All of the above</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">A supply curve is influenced by various factors including technology, input costs, and government regulation. Technology can affect production efficiency, input costs can change the cost of production, and government regulations can impose restrictions or incentives that affect supply. Therefore, the correct answer is 'All of the above'.</div>", "topic": "THEORY OF SUPPLY : MEANING AND DETERMINANTS"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2018 Model I>28", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Economics of scale describe</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the scale of the long run average cost curve</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">an input-output space</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">a long run situation</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">a state of production</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Economies of scale refer to the cost advantages that a business obtains due to the scale of operation, with cost per unit of output generally decreasing with increasing scale as fixed costs are spread out over more units of output. This is often represented by the long-run average cost curve, which shows how average costs change with different levels of output.</div>", "topic": "THEORY OF PRODUCTION : INTRODUCTION"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2018 Model I>29", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Marginal utility is equal to average utility at that time when average utility is</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Increasing</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Maximum</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Falling</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Minimum</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Marginal utility is equal to average utility when average utility is at its maximum. This is because when average utility is increasing, marginal utility is greater than average utility, and when average utility is falling, marginal utility is less than average utility. Therefore, option B is correct.</div>", "topic": "THEORY OF CONSUMER BEHAVIOUR : DIMINISHING MARGINAL UTILITY AND LAW OF DEMAND"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2018 Model I>30", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The demand curve facing a monopolist is </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">downward sloping</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">horizontal</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">upward sloping</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">kinked</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The demand curve facing a monopolist is typically downward sloping. This means that as the monopolist lowers the price, the quantity demanded increases, which is characteristic of most demand curves in economics. Hence, the correct answer is that the demand curve is downward sloping.</div>", "topic": "MARKET STRUCTURE : IMPERFECT MARKET - MONOPOLY"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2018 Model I>31", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">A market equilibrium exist when</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Demand and suppy are equal</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The market is large</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The price is fluctuating</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">No buyer goes home empty handed</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Market equilibrium occurs when the quantity of goods demanded by consumers equals the quantity of goods supplied by producers. At this point, the market is stable, and there is no tendency for the price to change. Therefore, the correct option is 'Demand and supply are equal'.</div>", "topic": "MARKET STRUCTURE : MEANING OF MARKET & TYPES"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2018 Model I>32", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">If your income during one year is #10,000 and the following year it is #12,000, then it has increased by</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">20%</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">2%</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">12%</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">16%</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">To calculate the percentage increase in income from #10,000 to #12,000, we use the formula: ((New Income - Old Income) / Old Income) * 100. This results in ((12,000 - 10,000) / 10,000) * 100 = 20%. Therefore, option A is correct.</div>", "topic": "BASIC CONCEPTS OF ECONOMICS"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2018 Model I>33", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">One of the reasons for low agricultural yields in Nigeria is</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Tribalism</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Religious differences</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Attitude of farmers towards the use of modern implements</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Constant change of government</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">One of the reasons for low agricultural yields in Nigeria is the attitude of farmers towards the use of modern implements. This reflects a reluctance to adopt new technologies that could enhance productivity. Therefore, the correct answer is the attitude of farmers towards modern implements.</div>", "topic": "AGRICULTURE"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2018 Model I>34", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Other things being equal, what causes a decrease in demand?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">rise in the price of the substitute</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">fall in the price of the commodity</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">rise in the income of the consumer</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">rise in the price of the commodity</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">A decrease in demand occurs when consumers are less willing or able to purchase a good or service at a given price. One of the primary factors that can lead to a decrease in demand is a rise in the price of the commodity itself. When the price of a good increases, consumers typically buy less of it, leading to a decrease in demand. This is known as the law of demand, which states that, all else being equal, an increase in the price of a good results in a decrease in the quantity demanded.</div>", "topic": "BASIC CONCEPTS OF ECONOMICS"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2018 Model I>35", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Which of the following defines the tools of economics analysis ?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Theorizing</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Abstracting</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Modeling</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">All of the above</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The tools of economic analysis include theorizing, abstracting, and modeling. Each of these methods is essential for understanding economic phenomena and making predictions about economic behavior.</div>", "topic": "METHODS OF ECONOMIC ANALYSIS"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2018 Model I>36", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Demand for a commodity refers to </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Need for a commodity </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Desire for a commodity </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Amount of a commodity demanded at a particular price and at a particular time</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Quantity demanded of that commodity</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Demand for a commodity is defined as the quantity of that commodity that consumers are willing and able to purchase at a given price and at a specific time. This definition encompasses the relationship between price and quantity demanded, making the correct answer the amount of a commodity demanded at a particular price and at a particular time.</div>", "topic": "BASIC CONCEPTS OF ECONOMICS"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2018 Model I>37", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">One of the following is a correct characteristic of the advanced market capitalist economy</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">proper distribution of income</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">a greater standard by the generality of the citizens</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">it is not prone to economic uncertainties and political upheavals</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the rich getting richer and the poor getting poorer</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">One of the correct characteristics of an advanced market capitalist economy is \"the rich getting richer and the poor getting poorer.\" In a market capitalist economy, where the means of production are primarily owned by private individuals or entities, there tends to be an unequal distribution of wealth and income. This characteristic often results in the concentration of wealth among a small portion of the population, leading to the rich getting richer. At the same time, those with fewer resources may struggle to improve their economic situation, resulting in the poor getting poorer. <br/>  <br/> It is important to note that this characteristic is not universally true for all market capitalist economies and can vary depending on various factors, including government policies, social safety nets, and economic conditions. Additionally, this characteristic is not necessarily exclusive to advanced market capitalist economies and can be observed in other economic systems as well.</div>", "topic": "ECONOMIC SYSTEM : TYPES AND FEATURES OF ECONOMIC SYSTEM"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2018 Model I>38", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">A foreign exchange market where there is the official operating side by side with the autonomous market is called</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the second tier</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">co-operation</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">foreign exchange market</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">foreign exchange currency</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The official market is the market where the central bank of a country operates. The autonomous market is the market where other participants, such as banks and businesses, operate. The second tier foreign exchange market is a market that is created when the official market and the autonomous market are allowed to operate side by side. <br/>  <br/> The second tier foreign exchange market can help to improve the efficiency of the foreign exchange market by providing more liquidity and competition. It can also help to reduce the volatility of the foreign exchange market by providing a more diversified pool of buyers and sellers.</div>", "topic": "INTERNATIONAL TRADE : EXCHANGE RATE"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2018 Model I>39", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the formula:  ∑x/n, n stands for</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The number of occurrences</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The number of frequencies</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The summation of the frequencies</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The summation of occurrences</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the formula, \"n\" stands for the number of observations or data points in the dataset. It represents the total number of individual data values or occurrences in the dataset, not the number of frequencies or the summation of frequencies or occurrences.</div>", "topic": "TOOLS FOR ECONOMIC ANALYSIS : MEASURE OF CENTRAL TENDENCY"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>2018 Model I>40", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The history of development planning in Nigeria started in</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">1960</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">1962</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">1970</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">1968</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The history of development planning in Nigeria started in 1962. The first Nigerian National Development Plan was launched in that year, with a six-year target that envisaged the spending of about $1,900,000,000 on development and productivity enhancing projects. <br/>  <br/> The plan was prepared by the Federal Ministry of Economic Development and Reconstruction, with the assistance of the United Nations Development Programme (UNDP). It was based on the principle of self-help and aimed to achieve self-sustained economic growth and development. <br/>  <br/> The plan was divided into three phases: <br/> - The first phase (1962-68) was to focus on infrastructure development, such as roads, railways, and power plants. <br/> - The second phase (1968-74) was to focus on agricultural development, such as irrigation, land reform, and agricultural research. <br/> - The third phase (1974-80) was to focus on industrial development, such as the development of new industries and the expansion of existing industries. <br/>  <br/> The first Nigerian National Development Plan was not fully implemented due to the outbreak of the Nigerian Civil War in 1967. However, it laid the foundation for future development planning in Nigeria. <br/>  <br/> Since 1962, Nigeria has implemented a total of 12 national development plans. The most recent plan is the 2021-2025 National Development Plan. <br/>  <br/> The 2021-2025 National Development Plan is a medium-term plan that aims to achieve inclusive growth and sustainable development in Nigeria. The plan is based on the following pillars: <br/>  <br/> Infrastructure development <br/> Human capital development <br/> Economic diversification <br/> Social inclusion <br/> Governance <br/>  <br/> The 2021-2025 National Development Plan is a ambitious plan that faces a number of challenges, including insecurity, corruption, and economic volatility. However, it is a necessary step for Nigeria to achieve its development goals.</div>", "topic": "ECONOMIC DEVELOPMENT : DEVELOPMENT PLANNING"}];
